objectives: 

    contracts are at the basis of majority of transactions especially transactions dealing with the property. 
    whether the transaction is in the ordinary course of life or in the electronic world (e-commerce) the general principles governing contracts remain same. 
    for this reason it is very important to introduce the students to the basic princiles governing contracts and lay a powerful foundation for their study of other transactional and related laws in subsequent semesters. 

unit 1: 
    formation of contracts
    agreement and contract
    definitions
    classification
    offer and acceptance
    communication
    revocation
        essential elements
    invitation to offer - tenders
    consideration - NudumPactum
        essential elements
    privity of contract and of consideration
    exceptions
    unlawful consideration and its effect
    e-contract

unit 2
    capacity to contract
    minor's agreements and its effects
    agreement of persons of unsound mind and persons disqualified by law
    free consent
    coercion
    undue influence
    misrepresentation
    fraud
    mistake
    legality of object
    void agreements
    contingent contract

unit 3
    modes of discharge of contracts
    time and place of performance
    performance of reciprocal promises
    appropriation of payments
    discharge by agreement
    operation of law
    frustration (impossibility of performance) and by breach (anticipatory and actual)

unit 4
    remedies for breach of contracts
    damages
    kinds of damages
    ascertainment of damages
    quasi contracts

unit 5
    The Specific Relief Act - Sections 9-16, Sections 21, Section 24, Sections 36-42
    nature of specific relief
    recovery of posession of movable and immovable property
    specific performance when granted and not granted
    who may obtain and against whom
    discretionary remedy
    power of court to grant relief
    rectification of instruments
    cancellation
    declaratory decrees
    preventive relief
    temporary injunctions
    perpetual and mandatory injunctions

books: 
    Law of Contract and Specific Relief - Avtar Singh (Eastern Book Company)

    Indian Contract and Specific Relief - Pollock and Mulla (lexis Nexis)
    Atiyah's Introduction to the Law of contract - Smith, Stephen A and P.S Atiyah
    Law of Contract - G.C. Cheshire and Fifoot (Lexis Nexis)
    Law of Contract - William Anson (Oxford University Press)
    Ancient Law - Henry, Maine (Albemarle Street)


Questions: 

    Unit 1 — Formation of contracts

        “All contracts are agreements, but all agreements are not contracts.” Explain the essentials of a valid contract.
        Define consideration; explain essentials and exceptions to privity of contract with cases (nudum pactum, past/adequate/third-party benefits, etc.).
        Offer & Acceptance—rules on communication and revocation; distinguish invitation to offer (tenders, display of goods); add a note on e-contracts.

    Unit 2 — Capacity & Free consent

        Minor’s agreement—legal position, enforceability, and effects with leading cases.
        Free consent: distinguish fraud and misrepresentation; effects on validity; remedies.
        Legality of object & void agreements (public policy, agreements in restraint of trade/marriage/legal proceedings) + brief note on contingent contracts.

    Unit 3 — Discharge & Performance

        Modes of discharge of contracts—by performance, agreement/novation, impossibility, operation of law, breach (anticipatory & actual).
        Doctrine of frustration—scope, limits, and leading cases.
        Performance of reciprocal promises; time and place of performance; appropriation of payments.

    Unit 4 — Breach, Damages & Quasi-contracts

        Remedies for breach—kinds of damages and ascertainment (remoteness, mitigation).
        Liquidated damages vs. penalty (Sec. 74) with case law; link to Hadley v Baxendale principles.
        Quasi-contracts—nature, categories (Sec. 68–72), and unjust enrichment rationale.

    Unit 5 — Specific Relief Act (Ss. 9–16, 21, 24, 36–42)

        Specific performance—when granted/not granted; who may obtain and against whom; discretionary nature; (touch on Sec. 21, 24 where relevant).
        Injunctions—temporary vs. perpetual vs. mandatory; when courts grant/refuse; preventive relief framework (Ss. 36–42).
        Rectification, cancellation, and declaratory decrees—nature, grounds, and court’s powers.








